🎬 Netflix Content Analysis using SQL Server (MSSQL)
This project explores the Netflix content dataset using Microsoft SQL Server. I solved multiple business-oriented SQL problems to uncover insights related to content type, genres, ratings, regional trends, and more.
📁 Dataset Fields
Includes details like:
show_id, type, title, director, cast, country, date_added, release_year, rating, duration, listed_in, description

✅ Business Questions Answered
Count the number of Movies vs TV Shows
Most common rating for Movies and TV Shows
Movies released in a specific year (e.g., 2020)
Identify the longest movie
Content added in the last 5 years
All content by director 'Rajiv Chilaka'
TV shows with more than 5 seasons
Count content items in each genre
Top 5 years with highest content released in India
List all documentaries
Content without a director
Count of movies featuring 'Salman Khan' in last 10 years
Classify content as 'Good' or 'Bad' based on keywords ('kill', 'violence')

🔧 SQL Concepts Used
Filtering with WHERE, LIKE, IS NULL
Aggregation: COUNT, AVG, MAX
Grouping and Ranking: GROUP BY, RANK()
String functions: STRING_SPLIT, LTRIM, RTRIM
Window functions: OVER()
CTEs (Common Table Expressions)

📊 Key Insights
Movies dominate the platform compared to TV Shows
Documentaries and Dramas are among the top genres
Indian content releases have increased significantly since 2018
Metadata inconsistencies like missing directors are present
Keyword tagging helps classify potentially violent content

🛠 Tools Used
SQL Server (MSSQL)
SSMS (SQL Server Management Studio)
